data.name: EulerIntegratorTb.Text
data.value:
The Euler method is a numerical method of integrating differential equations. The Semi-implicit Euler method that is used in the program is a modification of the Euler method for solving differential equations in classical mechanics. The fact that velocity is the rate of change of position / the rate of change of time suggests that to work out the position, we need to integrate the Delta position/ Delta time and Euler method does this exactly. Hence to approximate the velocity (from acceleration) and position (from velocity) we can use the Euler method. To do this we must use a timestep, the shorter the timestep, the more accurate our approximation is.
Therefore the default value of timestep I chose is 1/60. The table on the left shows different values of error for corresponding values of the timestep, as visibile, the lower the step, the lower the error.

data.name: CollisionsTB.Text
data.value:
Momentum in all particle-particle collisions is conserved. This means that if a heavier particle strikes a lighter particle, the lighter particle's velocity would be higher to obey the momentum equation : p = mv (where p is momentum, m is mass and v is velocity)
The equation of motion underneath is used to derive an angle free represntation. These equations have been taken from wikipedia.
